## Data Layer Patterns {#data-layer}

The data layer is the bridge between your website's code and GTM. Push structured data to it, then reference that data in GTM variables and triggers.

### Initialize the data layer

Place this before the GTM container snippet in your HTML head:

```html
<script>
  window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
</script>
```

### Push patterns

```javascript
// Simple event
dataLayer.push({
  'event': 'form_submitted',
  'form_name': 'contact',
  'form_location': 'footer'
});

// Event with user context
dataLayer.push({
  'event': 'checkout_started',
  'cart_value': 149.99,
  'cart_items': 3,
  'user_type': 'returning'
});

// Update user properties (no event trigger)
dataLayer.push({
  'user_id': 'USR_12345',
  'user_type': 'premium'
});

// Clear e-commerce data between pushes (prevents stale data)
dataLayer.push({ ecommerce: null });
dataLayer.push({
  'event': 'purchase',
  'ecommerce': {
    'transaction_id': 'T12345',
    'value': 99.99,
    'currency': 'USD',
    'items': [{ ... }]
  }
});
```

### Important: Always clear e-commerce objects

GA4 e-commerce events can bleed data between pushes if you do not clear the ecommerce object first. Always push `{ ecommerce: null }` before a new e-commerce event.

