## Server-Side GTM {#server-side}

### When to use server-side tracking

- Ad blockers are significantly reducing your data quality
- You need to control exactly what data leaves the browser
- Privacy requirements demand server-side processing
- You want to extend cookie lifetimes (first-party context)

### Architecture

Browser GTM container sends data to a server GTM container (hosted on your domain or a subdomain). The server container then forwards data to GA4, Google Ads, Meta, etc.

### Setup overview

1. Create a Server container in GTM
2. Deploy to Google Cloud (App Engine) or a custom hosting environment
3. Configure your web container to send data to the server container endpoint
4. Set up server-side tags for each destination (GA4, Ads, etc.)
5. Map and transform data as needed in the server container

Server-side GTM adds complexity and hosting costs. Only implement when the benefits clearly justify the overhead.

